{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01T73pBFpX1QiMwkhr1JDaa6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have everything I need. Let me also check the existing test to understand the `vi.hoisted` + `vi.mock` pattern being used in the route tests, specifically for how they mock modules imported by the route file.\n\nFrom the `events/list/__tests__/route.test.ts`, the pattern is:\n1. `vi.hoisted` to create mock functions\n2. `vi.mock(\"@/lib/identity\", ...)` to mock the module\n3. Import the route handler after the mocks\n4. Pass `Request` objects directly to the handler\n\nAnd from `events/__tests__/route.test.ts`:\n\n\n1. Similar pattern for mocking `@/lib/identity`\n\nFor my trends route test, I need to mock `@/lib/trends` and test the route handler. Now I'll implement everything: first the tests for both files, then the `src/lib/trends.ts` module, and finally the `src/app/api/trends/route.ts` handler. I need to be careful with the `computeEndExclusive` function for date arithmetic, the \"Other\" grouping in the breakdown, and properly constructing the Response object.\n\nLooking at the existing route patterns, `events/list` uses `Request` and `Response.json` while `schema` uses `NextResponse.json`. I'll follow the `events/list` pattern since it's most similar to what I'm building. For the test, I'll construct a `Request` and call the route handler the same way.\n\nWriting the test files and implementation now... Setting up test helpers and base parameters for the trends query tests, then defining the test suite structure with beforeEach and afterEach hooks to manage mock state.\n\nNow I'm writing test cases that verify the query builder generates the correct SQL expressions for different measure types—checking that count uses count(), unique_users uses uniqExact with identity mappings, and sum/avg measures use JSONExtractFloat with the appropriate aggregation function. Writing test cases... Writing test cases... Writing test cases... Writing test setup... Writing test cases... Writing test cases... Writing test cases... I'm checking the regex pattern for the measure validation—it requires at least one character after the colon, so `sum:` with nothing following wouldn't match and would correctly return an error. Now I'm looking at how the events list route handles responses.\n\nI notice the list route uses `Response.json` while the schema route uses `NextResponse.json`. Since `NextResponse` extends `Response` and the tests call `res.json()` directly, both should work fine, but I'll align with the list route for consistency.\n\nLooking at the test directory structure, I need to follow the pattern of placing tests in `__tests__` subdirectories alongside the routes. For the trends feature, that means `src/app/api/trends/__tests__/route.test.ts` and `src/lib/__tests__/trends.test.ts`. Let me start creating these files now.\n\nFor the `buildTrendsQuery` function, I'm checking how the ClickHouse parameters work—specifically whether passing ISO datetime strings as `{param:String}` types will properly cast to DateTime64 columns. Looking at the existing identity.ts implementation, it seems this pattern already works with timestamp comparisons.\n\nFor the start parameter, I'll format it as an ISO string with time component, and for the end_exclusive, I need to compute the day after the requested date and convert that to an ISO datetime string. ClickHouse should handle the string-to-DateTime64 casting automatically in the comparison operations.\n\nNow I'm checking the biome linter configuration to see if there are any specific formatting or style rules I should follow.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":504,"cache_read_input_tokens":60128,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":504},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inf